{{Infobox language |name = Solomon Islands Sign Language |altname = SISL |states = [[Solomon Islands]] |region = |speakers = ? |date= |ref= |familycolor = sign |family = indigenous&ndash; [[Auslan]] creole? creole of local regional languages? |iso3 = szs |glotto=none |glottorefname= }}
'''Solomon Islands Sign Language''' is the local [[deaf sign language]] of the [[Solomon Islands]]. There are significant between the sign of the main islands of [[Guadalcanal]] and [[Malaita]], and presumably elsewhere. The capital [[Honiara]], where deaf people from all nine provinces have gathered, has the most developed [[Deaf community]], and there is a nearby [[Deaf village]] at [[Aruliho]]. SISL is all domains of life, with admixture of [[Signed English]] and [[AUSLAN]] signs.<ref name=ISO/>
There is a relatively high incidence of deafness in the Solomon Islands due to poverty-related diseases such malaria, meningitis, rubella, and otitis media. Attitude towards SISL is very positive, and the community worries that AUSLAN, which is taught at school, does not reflect their cultural and language needs. This has been confirmed by a pilot linguistic investigation.<ref name=ISO>[http://www-01.sil.org/iso639-3/cr_files/2016-013_szs.pdf ISO 639-3 Registration Authority Request for New Language Code Element in ISO 639-3]</ref>
